The Spark API hierarchy.

Spark has three structured-data interfaces, in increasing order of abstraction.

At the bottom is the R-D-D — the original. It is functional and row-by-row, and crucially, it gets no Catalyst optimization and no Tungsten code generation.

In the middle is the dataframe — a distributed table with a schema. This is the everyday interface.

At the top is the dataset — a typed dataframe with compile-time type safety. But it is available in Scala and Java only.

In pyspark, you only ever get dataframes. Internally, a dataframe is just an alias for a dataset of rows — the same engine, without a static type parameter.

And here is the practical fact to carry forward. Sequel, the dataframe interface, and the Scala dataset all compile through Catalyst, and they produce identical execution plans. Only the R-D-D bypasses Catalyst — and that is exactly why the R-D-D is slower for structured data.
